      "host": "cimmagazine.com",
      "text": "Exhibitions a driver for growth and global trade By cim / October 24,   Exhibitions a driver for growth and global trade \nThe Association of Australian Convention Bureaux’s (AACB) latest analysis of international bids won, lost and in the pipeline shows the importance of exhibitions, with an estimated 125,000 international and 74,000 domestic delegates and potential buyers heading to Australia. Print AACB says exhibitions play a significant role in Australia’s economic growth \nAACB’s members secured 154 international business events that include an exhibition on the forward calendar, with a further 75 yet to confirm their exhibition requirements. The 68th International Astronautical Congress held in Adelaide brought new trade and business opportunities. \n“International exhibitions play a significant role in enabling global trade and stimulating Australia’s economy,” said Andrew Hiebl, CEO of the AACB. “They offer a platform for Australian small to medium enterprises to promote their goods and services to export markets on home soil. \n“Almost half of the international association conventions won have a confirmed exhibition. Without the strategic bidding activities of convention bureaux, these opportunities would simply not occur in Australia.” MCEC hosted the World Conference on Carbon 2017. \nThe top five industry sectors attracted for international business events are Healthcare and Social Assistance (1 in 4); Professional, Scientific and Technical Services (1 in 5); Information, Media and Telecommunications (1 in 10); Financial and Insurance Services (1 in 20); and Administrative and Support Services (1 in 20). \n“Business events enable opportunities for commercialisation by bringing together scientists and researchers with private enterprise and investors. Resulting new products and services then increase national productivity,” said Karen Bolinger, AACB’s president. \n“For many professions, exhibitions are a key sales tool, and in some instances, they are the primary marketing activity. As such, their value to cities that exert new technology cannot be underestimated.” The International Conference on Machine Learning was held at ICC Sydney in 2017. \nIn the last few months, significant international exhibitions accompanied conventions such as the 68th International Astronautical Congress (Adelaide), The World Conference on Carbon 2017 (Melbourne), and The International Conference on Machine Learning (Sydney). \nHiebl said that the losses are still a concern, however, the bid pipeline shows tremendous opportunity. \n“Unfortunately, Australia is still missing out on this significant opportunity for connecting with global industries,” he said. “Through these international bid losses, 94 exhibitions will now be held in countries other than Australia, putting access to basic trade opportunities out of reach for many Australian SMEs. \n“However, convention bureaux around the country continue to work with their industry partners on opportunities that remain in the bid pipeline, including up to 125 bids in play with exhibitions that present the potential for international trade.”",
