      "text": "ASBEC touts less focus on BCR, national guidelines in push for better business cases \nBy Patrick Lau, Monday 23 October 2017 The peak body for sustainable construction has called for better business case practices in Australian infrastructure, pointing out a culture of haphazard planning and communication. \nPoor planning and communication hamper Australian infrastructure, according to ASBEC The Australian Sustainable Built Environment Council (ASBEC), in a recent whitepaper titled \"Bang for Buck: Delivering better business cases to realise more value from our infrastructure investments\" , has collated the findings from a series of roundtable discussions with decision makers across government, industry and agencies connected to infrastructure planning and development. The results revealed a lack of coordination, mismanagement of data, and inconsistency of purpose when it comes to building business cases for infrastructure projects. ASBEC noted that many of its findings \"will be familiar to infrastructure policy and decision makers\". Chief among the areas of challenge that ASBEC reports are leadership, decision-making, understanding of methodology, and public engagement. However, \"Bang for Buck\" also includes specific recommendations to improve processes and outcomes. These solutions are largely at national and federal level, to integrate better practices across a sector plagued by miscommunication and cross-purposes. Vision and leadership are lacking in the arena of business case development, although ASBEC argues this is partially the fault of a lack of overarching policy. The whitepaper calls for \"a shared integrated vision for our cities and communities\" and \"clear indicators… [to] provide an anchor for business case development\". In terms of decision-making, treasuries are singled out for \"short-termism\" and \"a focus on reducing costs\"; while business cases for social infrastructure are impeded by the dominant transport infrastructure paradigm. In general, says ASBEC, the infrastructure industry focuses on project delivery rather than success or improvement, often failing to evaluate or actuate benefits. In response, it calls for statutorily independent agencies to review and report on business cases, while Infrastructure Australia should be handed responsibility for developing guidelines for business case development. All public stakeholders \"should embed project evaluation and benefit realisation within decision making processes, as a condition of funding and as a core component of project scoping\". But possibly the most damning criticism is saved for the section on method and \"madness\". The indictment of the Australian infrastructure sector's business case methodology is gleaned from ASBEC's discussions with industry and government leaders, and comes with the stamp of inside knowledge. According to these voices of authority, infrastructure business case development in Australia is a shambolic and amateurish process. A litany of sector failures is outlined. Guidelines are nonexistent or \"inconsistently applied across jurisdictions\"; costing and valuing risks is done wilfully rather than deliberately; discount rates are misunderstood or inflated. Externalities values are tied to international datasets, and other metrics differ arbitrarily between bodies and localities. Options analysis and whole-of-life costing are limited, and a \"reliance on benefit-cost ratios (BCR) creates a pass/fail culture for decision-makers that in and of itself motivates the delivery of a business case above a benefit-cost ratio of ‘1'\". \nThe proposed solution largely involves beefing up Infrastructure Australia through increased resources and responsibilities. The development of guidelines, including standardised metrics, and oversight of a national ‘community of practice' involving infrastructure stakeholders (\"treasuries, line agencies and infrastructure delivery bodies\"). The whitepaper also covers poor public engagement, noting that media reports often uncritically report BCR as the sum total of a business case. This comes at the expense of investigating the compromises made to reach a positive BCR, or the complexities of the business case surrounding it. In response, it argues: \"Business cases should support narratives for infrastructure decisions that communicate benefits\". Framing them within broader policy vision, and supporting them with intelligent and intelligible data, will push benefits to the forefront of public consciousness. \nWhile the proposals in \"Bang for Buck\" are extensive, it seems ASBEC is both serious and realistic about advancing them. The report implies forthcoming discussions with Australian parliaments and infrastructure agencies - and concludes by calling for the support of industry to bring weight to the issue. With several high-profile instances of contention in recent years - the NBN and various energy projects perhaps chief among them - it appears business cases for infrastructure are increasingly subject to scrutiny in the newsroom, parliaments and pubs alike. Standards of communication that go beyond BCR can only be a good thing, for the sake of informed debate if nothing else. LISTED UNDER TAG :",
      "main_image_url": "//www.insideconstruction.com.au/w-images/7347a6f7-6141-4fe7-a24d-f498d2e5b3bd/4/fill/ASBEClogo-350x250.jpg",
