      "title": "Women's soccer still has leg up: Kerr",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T03:22:08Z",
      "url": "https://www.racingandsports.com.au/en/sports-football/womens-soccer-still-has-leg-up-kerr-story-424155",
      "host": "racingandsports.com.au",
      "text": "Women's soccer still has leg up: Kerr The potential to play at the Olympics and a FIFA World Cup gives soccer a leg up over rival codes for young females, according to Matildas star Sam Kerr.\nSoccer has two big advantages over rival codes competing for the interest of young female athletes, and Matildas star Sam Kerr isn't afraid to spruik them.\nThey are the Olympics and the FIFA Women's World Cup.\nThe 24-year-old believes those two showpiece tournaments alone should make the round-ball game the most enticing option for girls in the suddenly competitive women's sport market in Australia.\nThe female sporting sector has grown significantly in recent years, with a number of major bodies seeing it as a crucial way to grow their participation and fan rates.\nBoth AFL and cricket have introduced semi-professional domestic women's leagues in recent years, while the NRL has increased their focus on grassroots and the Australian Jillaroos.\nBut Kerr said soccer still maintained a distinct advantage for young females trying to get into a sport.\n\"We have one up on AFL and other sports like that,\" she said.\n\"We get to play worldwide and compete at the Olympics and World Cups, which other sports can't do.\n\"I don't think you can compete with it. I don't know: Playing in the AFL grand final or being in the Olympics? You can answer that question for me.\"\nKerr has quickly become the golden girl of women's soccer in Australia.\nIn the past week she has been named the USA's National Women Soccer League's MVP and Australia's Sportswoman of the Year.\nThose gongs now sit alongside the W-League MVP award she won at Perth Glory last season, who she re-signed for last month.\nThe forward's success for the Matildas has also helped take them to No.6 in the world, following their two defeats of Brazil on home soil last month.\nOn Monday she claimed the W-League was close to matching the USA's prestigious NWSL in terms of quality, and expected interest to rise significantly when its 10th season kicked off on Friday night, off the back of its first collective bargaining agreement and the Matildas' success.\n\"I think at the moment the league is in a really good place,\" Kerr said.\n\"We're taking steps forward and the Matildas' success has helped that a lot.\n\"It's a professional league where people have to live up to expectations. There's a lot of pressure with that but I think it's great.\"\nOne area where the W-League doesn't have it over their rivals yet is financially.\nDespite the signing of their historic first CBA this year, the $10,000 minimum payment for players per season is still well below that of Super Netball and cricket's domestic women's leagues, and only marginally above the AFLW competition.",
