      "title": "High Court sets date for citizenship ruling on Barnaby Joyce and six MPs Daily Telegraph",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T08:57:13Z",
      "url": "http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/business/work/high-court-sets-date-for-citizenship-ruling-on-barnaby-joyce-and-six-mps/news-story/94233cc99336c0e40523aff42efaecd3",
      "host": "dailytelegraph.com.au",
      "text": "THE High Court is set to hand down its ruling on the dual citizenship cases of Barnaby Joyce and six other federal MPs on Friday.\nThe “citizenship seven\" will learn their fate at 2.15pm.\nThe High Court has allowed themselves two weeks to make the landmark ruling, which will throw Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull’s one-seat majority government into jeopardy if the Deputy Prime Minister is disqualified from sitting in Parliament.\nThe Nationals leader will have to fight a by-election for the seat of New England if he loses the case.\nIf Mr Joyce then loses the by-election, the Prime Minister will have to seek confidence and supply from crossbench MPs to maintain a minority government.\nmedia_camera Barnaby Joyce reacts will have to fight a by-election if he loses the citizenship case. Picture: AAP The earliest the by-election could be held is December 2, which will leave the Coalition without its one-seat majority for at least one sitting week.\nChief Justice Susan Kiefel had acknowledged there was public interest in making a ruling as soon as possible at the close of a three-day High Court hearing in Canberra earlier this month.\nThe High Court will also rule on the dual citizenship cases of Nationals senators Matt Canavan and Fiona Nash, Greens senators Scott Ludlum and Larissa Waters, independent Nick Xenophon and One Nation senator Malcolm Roberts on Friday.\nmedia_camera The “citizenship seven” will know their fate on Friday. Picture: AAP Solicitor-General Stephen Donaghue argued the government’s case that only Senator Roberts and Mr Ludlum should be disqualified from Parliament during the three-day hearing.\nThe saga was sparked in July by Mr Ludlum’s resignation for holding New Zealand citizenship.\nHe was quickly followed by Ms Waters, who revealed she also held Canadian citizenship.\nSenator Canavan was then the first high profile government member to announce he might also have questions over his citizenship status.\nHe stepped aside from Mr Turnbull’s frontbench while the High Court decided the case.\nMr Joyce then made the bombshell announcement that he might be a New Zealand citizen in August, sparking intense scrutiny of dozens of other MPs who could be dual citizens.\nSenators Roberts, Nash and Xenophon were then referred to the High Court as well.\nOriginally published as Citizenship chaos not over yet",
