      "title": "No FFA Cup final derby after Western Sydney Wanderers lose semi-final to Adelaide",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T11:39:10Z",
      "url": "http://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/western-sydney-wanderers/no-ffa-cup-final-derby-after-western-sydney-wanderers-lose-semifinal-to-adelaide-20171024-gz7h5n.html",
      "host": "smh.com.au",
      "text": "More \nA Sydney derby in the FFA Cup final will have to wait. \nInstead, the Sky Blues will face Adelaide United in next month's FFA Cup final after the Reds knocked Western Sydney Wanderers out with a 2-1 semi-final win at Campbelltown Stadium on Tuesday night The Wanderers failed to repeat their impressive performance in Saturday night's derby against Adelaide and a lethargic, disjointed performance was punished with an abrupt end to their hopes of a first domestic cup final. SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Off to the final: Adelaide coach Marco Kurz (right) celebrates with his players after victory over the Wanderers. \nA stunning long-range strike by Adelaide midfielder Daniel Adlung separated the two sides as the Reds remained on course to become the first team to win two FFA Cups, having lifted the trophy in the inaugural tournament in 2014. \nThey were gifted the opener in the 13th minute, when a miss-kick by Wanderers defender Jonathan Aspropotamitis was pounced upon by Johan Absolonsen. Adelaide's Danish midfielder calmly slotted the ball past goalkeeper Vedran Janjetovic to give the Reds an early lead. Related Articles Brillante finish: Sydney FC snatch dramatic draw against Wanderers \nThe Wanderers' frustration was summed up when Roly Bonevacia was fortunate to escape with only a yellow card when he raked his studs down the leg of Adelaide's Isaias Sanchez. The Spaniard returned serve with a heavy challenge on Bonevacia seconds later to follow him into the book. Fortune smiled on Aspropotamitis on what was a difficult night for the promising youngster. Having already been cautioned, he was lucky to finish the first half after a clumsy, late challenge wasn't punished with anything further than a foul. \nAt the other end, Western Sydney's best chances came from distance while they nearly snuck an equaliser in the dying seconds of the first half when Oriol Riera's header from deep came close to looping into the far corner. SHARE",
      "main_image_url": "http://www.watoday.com.au/content/dam/images/g/z/7/i/i/r/image.related.articleLeadwide.620x349.gz7h5n.png/1508844159031.jpg",
