      "host": "afr.com",
      "text": "Bob Geldof is no Strauss but if you want to hear him sing, you have to go to a concert. Matt Cardy Share on twitter by Myriam Robin In Cairns last Friday, an attempt to coax ageing rocker Sir Bob Geldof to play a tune for attendees of the 40th annual Property Congress resulted in the Live Aid founder dramatically exiting the stage, midway through an interview with ex- 60 Minutes journo-turned-corporate affairs adviser Tracey Curro.\n\"We scoured around Cairns to see if we could find a Gibson guitar — I don't think we found a Gibson, but we did find a guitar and given you have recently been on stage and music is what defines you, I wondered whether you could indulge us,\" Curro asked.\nTo which the answer was, well, a definitive \"no\".\n\"I am not going to indulge you because it's naff,\" said Sir Bob, a reliably colourful regular on the corporate speaking circuit. \"I do my things for a band. Why do you think I spent fucking hundreds of thousands in a studio — it's like asking Strauss, 'Do you think I can just knock one off?' … No … goodbye!!\"\nTo which he stepped off the stage, leaving a presumably gobsmacked Curro halfway through her interview in front of 450 people.\n Earlier, Geldof had the stage to himself, which he'd used to wax on about global politics from French President Emmanuel Macron to US President Donald Trump. He also had some observations about property, including that he'd been a squatter before buying his first home outright. We're not sure how relatable that was to the real estate types who'd turned out to hear him, but maybe they got off lightly. According to a March report in the London Mirror , Geldof was encouraged off the stage of a financial services conference by British journalist Gabby Logan after telling guests that the public hated them. The conference organisers said that they'd just run out of time … and not a moment too soon!",
