      "url": "http://www.afr.com/real-estate/court-knocks-back-rda-property-groups-additional-units-at-bronte-place-20171024-gz72td",
      "host": "afr.com",
      "text": "Bronte Place will stick to 21 units. Share on twitter Share on Google Plus by Su-Lin Tan The NSW Land & Environment Court has knocked back RDA Property Group's appeal to build seven more units at its Bronte Place mixed-use apartment project at the controversial former Bronte RSL site in Sydney's eastern suburbs.\nSubjected to years of public protests, RDA , led by former fashion identity Danny Avidan , was the last in a line of developers to take on the project at at 109-113 Macpherson Street , approved for 21 apartments last year.\nRDA lodged a revised development application in December, in accordance with the Local Environment Plan, but was refused by Waverley Council.\nAfter facing court with an appeal three weeks ago, Commissioner Dickson on Tuesday dismissed the appeal due to the solar impact the additional units could cause to existing approved units.\nAny revisions to height and other development potential should be made through a planning proposal rather than a revision to the council approval, the commissioner said.\n Mr Avidan said he accepted the decision and would push on with the project, which has already been delayed.\n\"I respectfully accept the court's decision despite the fact that I disagree with the findings. I will proceed with the current approvals,\" he said.\nThe project is on a 2231 sq m site with ground-floor retail space, and is close to Bronte Beach.\nThe community, led by the Save Bronte group, protested the developer's decision to vary the 21-unit low-rise approval.",
