      "title": "Grace Under Pressure examines the daily lives of medical professionals",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T02:21:13Z",
      "url": "http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/theatre/grace-under-pressure-examines-the-daily-lives-of-medical-professionals-20171022-gz61em.html",
      "host": "theage.com.au",
      "text": "Can a doctor give a patient the best possible care if he or she hasn't eaten for hours? What if that doctor is also being bullied or sexually harassed at work or being pressured to work excessive hours? What if they haven't slept for days?\nThese are just some the questions raised in a new verbatim theatre production, Grace Under Pressure , which examines the working lives of health professionals and asks: \"Who is caring for those in the caring professions?\"\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Renee Lim: Under pressure to balance being a human being with being a doctor.  Photo: Louie Douvis Performed by four actors playing 18 characters, the script is based on hours of interviews with 30 doctors and nurses who spoke in-depth about their experiences of training and working in hospitals.\n\"There are lots of stories of exhaustion and working extremely long hours,\" says writer-director David Williams, who created the show with the University of Sydney's Paul Dwyer in collaboration with the Sydney Arts and Health Collective.\n\"People can be so tired that they have car accidents on the way home from night shifts. People can be on call overnight after they've worked all day. They get called in and they don't sleep but are expected to come back the next day.\"\nFor actor Renee Lim, the stories are close to home – she is also a doctor working in palliative care and accident and emergency.\nAdvertisement \"For me and my friends, one of the biggest pressures is how to balance being a human being with being a doctor,\" she says. \"How do you get through a day and eat enough and drink enough and go to the toilet at least twice, which is what normal people do, then also see the 37 patients they need to check on and make sure they don't die.\"\nAdd to all that the pressure of \"wanting to be perfect\", Lim says. \"So many doctors entering the profession want to be perfect, to save people and change the world. Then they find the system disempowers them.\"\nYou will now receive updates from Entertainment Newsletter Entertainment Newsletter Get the latest news and updates emailed straight to your inbox.\nBy submitting your email you are agreeing to Fairfax Media's terms and conditions and privacy policy . \nSome of the doctors and nurses Williams interviewed had dropped out of the hospital system to work in general practice or private care facilities. \"They found the pressure of the hospital system untenable but they loved the care element of it,\" Williams says.\n\"There are people who struggle with depression. Some get help and that help works. Some seek help and that help doesn't work or isn't offered. There have been lots of stories about health professionals or clinical staff who have felt unsupported to the extent that they have taken extreme measures: going public with sexual harassment or in some cases taking their own life.\"\nReports from Beyond Blue have suggested rates of clinical depression, suicidal ideation and suicidal behaviour among doctors and nurses are twice as high as in the general population.\nLim hopes audiences coming to see Grace Under Pressure will be reminded of their humanity. \"I hope people walk away going, 'wow, doctors are human beings too'. They can be broken, they can be wrong, they care and they are trying their best. We are all in this together. How you deal with a human being the next day, is something you can choose.\"\nGrace Under Pressure plays at the Seymour Centre from October 25-28. It is part of The Big Anxiety- Festival of Arts + Science + People.",
