      "score": 1,
      "title": "Adelaide Festival 2018 taps into FOMO with a suite of modern classics",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T04:46:45Z",
      "url": "http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/stage/adelaide-festival-2018-taps-into-fomo-with-a-suite-of-modern-classics-20171024-gz6xhc.html",
      "host": "theage.com.au",
      "text": "It was the talk of the town, the production that changed people. It was like nothing the city had seen before. Five stars wasn't enough.\nBut you missed it. Oops.\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link The Far Side of the Moon returns to Australia after 17 years.  Photo: Supplied You can see Shakespeare just about any day of the week, but can you see Robert Lepage's modern theatre classic The Far Side of the Moon ?\nActually, if you go to Adelaide Festival next year you can.\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Hotel Modern & Arthur Sauer's The Great War re-enacts World War I live in miniature.  Photo: Joost van den Broek \"We were interested in exploring the idea of contemporary classics, particularly in theatre,\" says Rachel Healy, whose tenure as co-artistic director alongside Neil Armfield has just been extended to 2021.\n\"Some of the really great works of our generation don't necessarily get revisited in the way classical music or opera, for example, does.\"\nAdvertisement Far Side of The Moon, a one-man play about two very different brothers dealing with the loss of their mother, set against the backdrop of the US-Soviet space race and with a soundtrack by Laurie Anderson, hasn't stopped touring since its premiere in 2000. \nYou will now receive updates from Entertainment Newsletter Entertainment Newsletter Get the latest news and updates emailed straight to your inbox.\nBy submitting your email you are agreeing to Fairfax Media's terms and conditions and privacy policy . \nAlso on the bill is Olivier Award-winning Simon Stone's Tarantino-esque interpretation of Thyestes , which this author missed when it stormed Melbourne in 2010 before being picked up by Sydney Festival. All a colleague felt fit to reveal about it was \"spaghetti and meatballs\".\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link The Hayloft Project's Thyestes comes to Adelaide after more than 15 years since its Melbourne and Sydney runs.  Photo: Jeff Busby Dutch outfit Hotel Modern's The Great War, which premiered in 2001, comes to Australia for the very first time. It's a visceral journey into World War I re-enacted live on camera in miniature.\n\"These are works that have a stream in festivals and shaped the course of theatre and art, and we are grabbing them in their authentic, original form,\" says Armfield. \"It really informs the audience ... [by] looking at the inheritance of those works, and that makes a really interesting and valuable proposition.\"\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Kings of War puts Shakespeare in a contemporary context.  Photo: Jan Versweyveld Healy says: \"These are the kinds of performances that you just remember for decades because they're just so incredible.\" \nAs with Lepage's offering, much of The Great War 's magic lies in its technical ingenuity. Decades on, even as technology has advanced and theatremakers have developed and improved on design foundations (including Lepage, who brought his absolute feat of intricacy, 887 , to the Melbourne Festival last year), Healy and Armfield say these productions still pack a massive punch.\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Akram Khan will perform his final solo work at Adelaide Festival.  Photo: Supplied \"At the very centre of this piece [ Far Side of the Moon ] is a very simple theatrical imagination,\" says Healy. \"When you strip away all that other [technical] stuff – as terrific as it is – you will get a work that is timeless, and that's why it has continued to find audiences.\" (The show has toured 45 countries in 17 years.)\nLike Thyestes , other theatre offerings in the 2018 festival program follow a trend of fresh twists on canonical classics, many of them with epic considerations.\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link US jazz singer Cecile McLorin Salvant.  Photo: Hector Perez Following the success of The Secret River at this year's festival, Armfield again fills the director's chair for Brett Dean's operatic version of Hamlet in its Australian premiere.\nInternationally acclaimed Belgian director Ivo van Hove brings Kings of War, an abridged medley of Shakespearean plays transposed into the present, in the same vein as his previous 2014 festival standout Roman Tragedies . \nA world premiere staging of British poet Alice Oswald's Memorial , a co-commission with the Melbourne Festival starring Helen Morse, re-imagines The Iliad through the eyes of hundreds slain in more recent wars.\nAnd Akram Khan, one of the world's best-known dancers, will perform his final full-length solo work, Xenos , which explores the myth of Prometheus from the perspective of an Indian colonial soldier in World War I.\nIn another promising trend, Patricia Cornelius – who until recently was Australia's most acclaimed playwright never to be commissioned on a main stage – is finally in the club with In The Club, a State Theatre Company of South Australia world premiere that deals with the topical issue of gendered violence in sporting teams.\n\"It's like the balance of the scales have tipped and everyone has realised what they've been missing out on [from Patricia],\" says Armfield. \"Curiously, within six months three different state theatre companies have commissioned her.\n\"This is clearly a work which is right in the centre of the popular imagination and at the centre of the news cycle: what happens between young men when they're glorified and turned into gods by their community?\"\nIn music, the festival has upsized Britain's Lost and Found Orchestra with an ensemble of hundreds of local performers playing handmade and \"found object\" instruments, which will perform outdoors.\nGrace Jones returns to Adelaide for one night only for the first time in 36 years; young American jazz prodigy Cecile McLorin Salvant has her Australian debut; and choral ensemble Rundfunkchor Berlin's Human Requiem sees singers rove and mingle in the audience while singing Brahms, in a uniquely immersive concert experience.\nAdelaide Festival is on March 2-18. adelaidefestival.com.au \n0 comments Log in to comment New User? Sign up \nYou are logged in as unknown Logout \n300 words\nClose comment form Write your comment here Screen name (required) Location (optional) I understand that submission of this content is covered by the Conditions of Use by which I am bound and Commenting Guidelines are available for my reference. \nClose Thank you Your comment has been submitted for approval. Please note that comments are moderated and are generally published if they are on-topic and not abusive. Sort comments by Oldest Newest",
