      "title": "Brad Hogg back rivals to Melbourne Renegades teammate Matthew Wade for spot in Test team",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T08:57:13Z",
      "url": "http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/cricket/brad-hogg-back-rivals-to-melbourne-renegades-teammate-matthew-wade-for-spot-in-test-team-20171024-gz7f4m.html",
      "host": "canberratimes.com.au",
      "text": "Veteran spinner Brad Hogg has pushed for Melbourne Renegades teammate Matthew Wade to be dropped from the Australian Test team, urging the national selectors to back in the younger Alex Carey, provided the South Australian wicketkeeper performs in the early rounds of the Sheffield Shield.\nThe keeper spot in Australia's XI for the first Ashes Test is up for grabs, with incumbent Wade, 29, under pressure to hold his position. Carey, 26, and Peter Nevill, 32, who made way for Wade late last year, are viewed as two the most likely replacements for Wade if the selectors opt to make a change.\nSpeaking on SEN's The Run Home on Tuesday, Hogg – who has signed to play again for the Big Bash League's Renegades, despite approaching his 47th birthday – threw his support behind Carey, and to a lesser extent Nevill, who played with Hogg at the Renegades last summer, but has since moved to the Sydney Sixers.\n\"As far as I'm concerned, if Alex Carey from South Australia does a good job, gets runs on the board early on, I think they should go 'Alex, that's your spot for a number of years' because the keeper's the one that gives you the energy out in the middle,\" Hogg said.\n\"He's the one that can direct traffic, help the captain out, so if you can have a keeper that's stable, there for the long run, keeps the energy up, I think they should be looking at a keeper for the long-term, not the short-term.\n\"I'd love [Peter] Nevill to get back in there, I think he had a great year there last year.\n\"Whoever makes those runs early on should get in there. I think it's between Nevill and Carey at the moment.\n\" 'Wadey', he's had a little bit of a rough patch in the subcontinent. He'd like to have a run in Australian conditions as well.\"\nWade, Nevill and Carey are all set to stake their claims for a berth in the Brisbane Test XI when the Shield season begins later this week.",
