      "title": "AWU GetUp raids: AFP probe union’s Melbourne and Sydney offices Daily Telegraph",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T08:51:24Z",
      "url": "http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/federal-police-raid-awus-melbourne-and-sydney-offices/news-story/a8db0d7352f6c771e6e06e4c6f6910cf",
      "host": "dailytelegraph.com.au",
      "text": "THE Australian Federal Police has raided the headquarters of the Australian Workers’ Union in Melbourne and Sydney.\nThe Herald Sun understand the raids, which began shortly after 4pm, were ordered in relation to a Registered Organisations Commission investigation.\nPlain-clothed AFP officers arrived at the union’s West Melbourne offices on Spencer St about 4.45pm and remain inside.\nAWU Victoria branch secretary Ben Davis told the Herald Sun he was disappointed with the decision to raid the building.\n“The AFP have turned up unannounced with a search warrant looking for various documents pertaining to an investigation by the Registered Organisations Commission,” he said.\nmedia_camera Australian Federal Police officers raid the offices of the AWU on Spencer St. Picture: Aaron Francis/The Australian media_camera Victorian AWU branch secretary Ben Davis outside the West Melbourne offices being raided by federal police. Picture: Jason Edwards\n“This is a shameful abuse of process which both the ROC and the Federal Government should be ashamed of themselves.\n“We have always provided any document that the Trade Union Royal commission and the ROC have always requested.\n“Had we been asked in the last 96 hours for these documents we would have done so and instead they have gone for the circus of involving the AFP.\n“This is an abuse of power, it is an abuse of process (and) you have not heard the end of this.”\nmedia_camera Victorian AWU branch secretary Ben Davis says the federal police raids are “an abuse of power”. Picture: Jason Edwards\nAWU national secretary Daniel Walton said the raids were an “extraordinary abuse of police resources and taxpayer funds by a desperate government”.\n“It is clear the ROC has been established not to promote good governance, but to use taxpayer and police resources to muckrake through historic documents in an attempt to find anything that might smear a future Labor PM,” Mr Walton said.\n“This is a shameful new low for a government already scraping the bottom of the political barrel.”\nMr Walton said more than 26 AFP officers were looking for documents dating back to 10 years ago in both Sydney and Melbourne.\nmedia_camera Australian Federal Police officers raid AWU headquarters in Sydney. Picture: James Croucher media_camera Australian Federal Police arrive to raid the Australian Workers Union offices on Sussex St in Sydney. Picture: Hollie Adams/The Australian\n“These documents relate to a number of donations that the union made to GetUp! and made to the Australian Labor Party,” he said.\n“The AWU has and always will cooperate with any investigation.\n“However the investigation which has been commenced today is nothing but an abuse of power.\n“(The documents) do nothing more than highlight the fact that the union made a couple of political donations.”\nLawyers representing the AWU will front the Melbourne Magistrates’ Court to plead their case about the use of AFP powers.\nACTU secretary Sally McManus said the raids were a “shocking attack on democracy”.\n“It just shows how far this government will go to attack working people,” she said.\nmedia_camera Australian Federal Police officers raid AWU headquarters in Sydney. Picture: James Croucher\nLabor workplace relations spokesman Brendan O’Connor said the raids were “an alarming misuse of ministerial power”.\n“Turnbull and his Government openly directed the Commission to start this witch hunt,” he said.\n“The Liberals have already wasted millions of taxpayers’ dollars on their witch hunt into unions.”\n“They will stop at nothing to attack workers and their representatives.”\n“This is the NBN raids during the election campaign all over again. Australians will see this for the desperate tactic that it is.”\nmedia_camera Australian Federal Police arrive to raid the Australian Workers Union offices on Sussex St in Sydney. Picture: Hollie Adams/The Australian media_camera Australian Federal Police officers raid the offices of the AWU on Spencer St. Picture: Aaron Francis/The Australian\nVictorian Trades Hall Council secretary Luke Hilakari said the raids were a “disgrace”.\n“ROC inappropriately using AFP resources. Turnbull is trying to destroy the voices of Aust workers,” he tweeted.\nLabor MP Stephen Jones told the ABC it was “quite clear a request has come down from the Minister’s office to chase this down”.\nA disgrace. Media alerted before union. ROC inappropriately using AFP resources. Turnbull is trying to destroy the voices of Aust workers\n— Luke Hilakari (@lhilakari) October 24, 2017 The investigation is probing the Victorian AWU and national branches over whether donations made to activist GetUp! in 2006 were approved under the union’s rules.\nAt the time Oppositions Leader Bill Shorten was the head of the AWU and the investigation is expected to probe whether these donations were made within the unions rules and regulations.\nMore to come\nOriginally published as Federal police raid AWU offices",
