      "host": "theage.com.au",
      "text": "Sir Henry in Tenterfield \nSir Henry Parkes said in his oration at the Tenterfield School of Arts that \"it was essential to preserve the security and integrity of these colonies that the whole of their forces should be amalgamated into one great federal army …the time was close at hand when they ought to set about creating this great national government for all Australia\" – in the words of poet Brunton Stephens, \"Not yet her day! How long?\"\nOne penny postal cards \n\"The Postal Department … received an intimation from the New Zealand Government to the effect that it had adopted the suggestion that penny postal cards posted from any part of Victoria should be delivered in any part of New Zealand without extra charge. The change will come into operation on November 1, when postal cards will be delivered throughout the whole of Australia without additional postage.\"\nBurial place unearthed \nThe burial place of Jethro Tull, the inventor of drilling and horseshoeing, was finally discovered in Basildon, UK. He lived at Shalbourne in Berkshire but no trace of him could be found in the parish register. An extract from a register published in Mr Money's \"Stray Notes of the Parish of Basildon\" states that he was buried 9 March, 1740-1, and was the author of a valuable book on agriculture titled Horse Husbandry.",
