      "text": "twitter TWEET More \nMyer's outgoing chairman says there would be no value in giving Solomon Lew seats on the department store's board, and has described the veteran retailer's meddling in the company as a \"train wreck\". \nIt comes after Mr Lew's Premier Investments drastically stepped up its attack on the company on Tuesday by threatening to call an extraordinary general meeting to win board seats, and calling on fellow shareholders to vote against the appointment of Myer's new chairman and other appointments at next month's AGM. SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Solomon Lew drastically stepped up his attack on Myer, threatening to call an early general meeting to get board seats. \n\"If he genuinely was seeking to build some sort of relation with the company, he couldn't have done it worse,\" Myer chairman Paul McClintock told Fairfax Media. \n\"The behaviour of Premier since they arrived has been aggressive and disruptive, and I think the chances of actually being able to incorporate a representative of that group in the company, and expect the board to keep a sense of cohesion and a sense of unity with the management… I think it would be serious disruption, and I see no value in doing so.\" Related Articles Myer chairman says 500,000 shares shows 'conviction' \nPremier Investments, Myer's largest investor with 10.8 per cent of shares, on Tuesday revealed Mr Lew met Myer's incoming chairman Garry Hounsell on October 6 to ask for two board seats and the appointment of a independent non-executive director. \nThe request was refused, and six days later Myer appointed to the board Julie Ann Morrison, who Premier pointedly described as a former director of Myer's \"failed\" Sass & Bide business. Advertisement \n\"Mr Hounsell then inferred to the media that he was yet to meet with Mr Lew,\" Premier said in a statement to the ASX. You will now receive updates from Business AM Newsletter Business AM Newsletter \nGet the latest news and updates emailed straight to your inbox. By submitting your email you are agreeing to Fairfax Media's terms and conditions and privacy policy . \nMr McClintock said Premier had no right to board representation, and that there would be conflict of interests given Premier and other companies linked to Mr Lew were major competitors and suppliers to Myer. \nAsked why conflicts of interest could not be dealt with under related party rules, Mr McClintock said: \"But why would you?\" \n\"They have ambitions of effectively taking control of the company. The basic rule of any ASX chairman is to make sure that if people outside want to take control of the company, they pay a proper premium and every shareholder gets the benefit.\" \nMr McClintock said that far from refusing access to Mr Lew as Premier has alleged, he had twice invited Mr Lew to meet the whole Myer board. The offers were declined, Mr McClintock said. \n\"When you stand in front of Mr Lew, traditionally you have a pretty good idea of what's going to happen,\" he said. \"I think this has been a train wreck that has been coming for a while, and we're dealing with it professionally. \nWhen you stand in front of Mr Lew, traditionally you have a pretty good idea of what's going to happen. Paul McClintock, Myer chairman \n\"The real issue here is, is there any justification in a company like Premier being given a very large measure of control over an ASX listed company, and if so why would you do that?\" \nMr Lew said in a letter to fellow Myer shareholders on Tuesday that \"enough is enough\" and that Myer's board needed the retail experience Premier could offer. \n\"How can the directors possibly advise management and keep them on their toes?\" Mr Lew said. \n\"As Myer shareholders we deserve better. Myer customers deserve better. The Australian fashion industry deserves better.\" \nPremier would reserve the right to call an extraordinary general meeting in the short term so shareholders could vote on its own nominees, it said. Related Articles",
