      "title": "Federal Police raid AWU offices in Sydney and Melbourne",
      "country": "AU",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T06:32:07Z",
      "url": "http://www.theage.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/federal-police-raid-awu-offices-in-sydney-and-melbourne-20171024-gz7b43.html",
      "host": "theage.com.au",
      "text": "Federal police are raiding the Sydney and Melbourne offices of Bill Shorten's old union, the Australian Workers Union, over donations made a decade ago to activist group GetUp!\nThe raids are under way at the union's Victorian office in Spencer Street, Melbourne and the National Office in Sussex Street, Sydney.\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Opposition Leader Bill Shorten is a former secretary of the AWU.  Photo: JAMES DAVIES The Turnbull government's newly established Registered Organisations Commission announced last Friday that it had begun investigating donations made by the AWU's National and Victorian offices to GetUp! back in 2006, and to other recipients during the 2008 financial year.\nAt the time, the Commission stated: \"the investigation relates to whether donations made to GetUp Limited during the financial year ending 2006 were approved under the AWU's Rules and separately, whether donations to a range of recipients during the financial year ending 30 June 2008 were approved under the AWU's Rules\".\nSHARE Share on Facebook SHARE Share on Twitter TWEET Link Paul Oosting, National Director of GetUp!  Photo: Peter Braig \"The AFP carried out the raids after the Commission had applied for and been granted a warrant for the raid.\"\nThe AWU's rules state that donations of more than $1000 must be approved by the national executive of the union.\nAdvertisement Some of the donations being examined include $100,000 paid by the AWU national office to Getup! in 2007-08, and $25,000 paid by the AWU national office to Mr Shorten's campaign for the seat of Maribyrnong in 2007-08.\nYou will now receive updates from Breaking News Alert Breaking News Alert Get the latest news and updates emailed straight to your inbox.\nBy submitting your email you are agreeing to Fairfax Media's terms and conditions and privacy policy . \nTwo other donations - $20,000 to Stirling and $25,000 to Petrie - by the AWU in that same election are being examined.\nMr Shorten was head of the AWU from 2001 until August 2007 and a former director of GetUp!\nThe raids on the offices of his former union and the question marks over the donations will create a new headache for Mr Shorten over his union past, which was examined in close detail by the Heydon royal commission.\nEmployment Minister Michaelia Cash referred the donations to the Commission back in August.\nAustralian Workers Union national secretary Daniel Walton said: \"This is an extraordinary abuse of police resources and taxpayer funds by a desperate government\".\n\"It is clear the ROC has been established not to promote good governance but to use taxpayer and police resources to muckrake through historic documents in an attempt to find anything that might smear a future Labour Prime Minister.\n\"This is a shameful new low for a government already scraping the bottom of the political barrel.\"\nMore to come",
      "main_image_url": "http://www.theage.com.au/content/dam/images/g/h/p/a/v/a/image.related.articleLeadwide.620x349.gz7b43.png/1508826668383.jpg",
